content:
Certainly! You can achieve this by using HTML along with some inline CSS for styling. To display the phrase "artificial intelligence" in bold and red, and also include a tooltip with a definition, you can use the following code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Artificial Intelligence</title>
    <style>
        .tooltip {
            position: relative;
            display: inline-block;
        }

        .tooltip .tooltiptext {
            visibility: hidden;
            width: 220px;
            background-color: #555;
            color: #fff;
            text-align: center;
            border-radius: 5px;
            padding: 5px 0;
            position: absolute;
            z-index: 1;
            bottom: 125%; /* Position the tooltip above the text */
            left: 50%;
            margin-left: -110px;
            opacity: 0;
            transition: opacity 0.3s;
        }

        .tooltip:hover .tooltiptext {
            visibility: visible;
            opacity: 1;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<p>
    The field of <span class="tooltip" style="font-weight: bold; color: red;">artificial intelligence
        <span class="tooltiptext">Artificial Intelligence is the simulation of human intelligence processes by machines, especially computer systems.</span>
    </span> is rapidly evolving.
</p>

</body>
</html>
```

Here's a breakdown of the code:

- The `<span>` element is used to wrap the phrase "artificial intelligence" and apply the styles directly to it.
- The `style` attribute is used to make the text bold and red.
- The `tooltip` class is used to apply the tooltip functionality.
- A nested `<span>` with the class `tooltiptext` contains the definition and is styled to appear when the user hovers over the main text.
